          "text": "Here's what I found. Two separate leaks in `mdns_sd.rs:156-169`:\n\n```rust\nlet hostname = hostname::get()...;              // e.g. \"leos-macbook\"\nlet instance_name = format!(\"{hostname}-{}\", std::process::id()); // \"leos-macbook-12345\"\nlet host_fqdn = format!(\"{hostname}.local.\");   // \"leos-macbook.local.\"\n```\n\n1. **Instance name** (`leos-macbook-12345`) — visible to any mDNS browser on the LAN. Leaks hostname + PID.\n2. **Host FQDN** (`leos-macbook.local.`) — the A/AAAA record target in the SRV record. Also leaks hostname.\n\nThe instance name is used downstream as an opaque key — `controller.rs` uses it for `peer_index` lookups and `lan:{instance_name}` labels, but never parses it.\n\nNow, the constraints:\n- **Instance name must be unique** on the LAN (mDNS-SD requirement — collisions cause confusion)\n- **Instance name should be stable across restarts** for the same node (so the controller doesn't treat a restart as a new peer + lost peer)\n- **Host FQDN must resolve** — `enable_addr_auto()` handles this, but `mdns-sd` uses it to register A/AAAA records\n- The **routing key is already in TXT records** — so the instance name doesn't need to carry identity info\n\nHere are three approaches:\n\n### Approach A: Truncated hash of routing key\n\n```rust\nlet instance_name = format!(\"reme-{}\", &hex::encode(&routing_key)[..12]);\n// e.g. \"reme-deadbeef0123\"\n```\n\n- Derives from the routing key (already public in TXT records, so no new info leaked)\n- Stable across restarts (same identity = same name)\n- Unique per identity (routing key is a BLAKE3 hash)\n- Requires passing routing key into `start_advertising` (it's already in `AdvertisementSpec.txt_records`, just needs extraction or a new field)\n\n### Approach B: Random instance name, persisted\n\n```rust\nlet instance_name = format!(\"reme-{}\", generate_random_8_chars());\n// Persist to disk so it's stable across restarts\n```\n\n- No correlation to any identity\n- Maximum p