ences the issue.\n\n---\n\n### Correctness analysis\n\n**Privacy goal achieved.** The hostname and PID are no longer broadcast. The routing key is already published in TXT records (via `encode_txt`), so deriving the instance name from it leaks no additional information. This is the right tradeoff noted in the plan.\n\n**Instance name uniqueness.** The instance name `reme-{32-hex-chars}` is deterministic per identity. This means:\n- Two clients with different identities on the same machine produce different instance names (correct).\n- The same client always produces the same instance name across restarts (correct -- and actually an improvement over the old PID-based scheme, which caused unnecessary service churn on restart).\n\n**Host FQDN collision.** The host FQDN `reme-{rk_hex}.local.` is tied to the routing key, not the actual machine. Since `mdns-sd` is called with `enable_addr_auto()` (empty string for host IP, auto-resolve), this is fine -- the FQDN is only used within the mDNS scope and does not need to resolve via DNS.\n\n---\n\n### Suggestions (nice to have, not blocking)\n\n1. **Routing key is a stable identifier across sessions.** The old hostname+PID changed on every restart, providing weak unlinkability across sessions. The new routing-key-derived name is persistent and allows a passive observer to track a specific identity across restarts and even across different networks. This is acknowledged in the issue (\"low impact for trusted-LAN\") and is the correct tradeoff for this project phase. However, if metadata resistance becomes a goal later, consider hashing the routing key with a per-session random salt (e.g., `reme-{hex(blake3(rk || session_nonce))[..16]}`). This would preserve privacy while preventing cross-session linkability. Worth a follow-up issue if the threat model evolves.\n\n2. **`RoutingKey` type coupling.** The `types.rs` file now imports `crate::txt::RoutingKey` (a `[u8; 16]` alias). This is a reasonable choice that keeps `reme-discove